        <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡¹ðŸ‡³ Tunisia opposition figures stand trial on national security charges</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            The trial of around 40 high-profile Tunisian opposition figures on national security charges started on Tuesday. Rights groups <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-03-2025-r1-1-condemn-it-as-politically-motivated" target="_blank">condemn it as politically motivated</a>. The defendants face accusations of "plotting against state security" and "belonging to a terrorist group." Some of these charges could lead to capital punishment. The defendants include former diplomats, politicians, lawyers, and media figures. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            President Kais Saied was re-elected in 2024 amid a record-low turnout, with many opposition figures jailed or barred from running. Some of the defendants have called the trial "judicial harassment," while others have been in detention since 2023. The UN urges Tunisia to end arbitrary arrests and detentions. However, the Tunisian government dismissed the concerns.  
          </p>
          </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡·ðŸ‡¸ Serbia's opposition smokes and flares a protest in parliament</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          Serbiaâ€™s parliament erupted in chaos as <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-03-2025-r2-2-opposition-mps-fired-smoke-bombs" target="_blank">opposition MPs fired smoke bombs</a>. This was in protest against alleged government corruption. Police are investigating, and President Aleksandar Vucic condemned the incident as "hooliganism." The unrest follows mass demonstrations sparked by a railway station collapse in November that killed 15 people.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
          The collapse fuels accusations of corruption in government projects. Students have led demonstrations demanding transparency, joined by workers from various sectors. Vucicâ€™s Serbian Progressive Party has dominated elections since 2012. The opposition parties remain divided. Protesters seek a technical government to ensure fair elections, but Vucic rejects this. With larger protests planned, political tensions in Serbia continue to escalate.
          </p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px; line-height:1.2;">
          <strong>ðŸ‡¹ðŸ‡­ The US offered to resettle Uyghurs that Thailand deported to China</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
            Thailand recently deported 48 ethnic Uyghurs to China despite offers from the US, Canada, and Australia to resettle them. Thailand resisted these offers, fearing <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-03-2025-r3-3-a-diplomatic-fallout-with-china" target="_blank">a diplomatic fallout with China</a>, its largest trade partner. The UN had warned that deportation could lead to torture or ill-treatment. Thailand maintained it acted per laws and human rights obligations.
          </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"> 
           The Uyghurs were detained in Thailand for over a decade. They were denied asylum processing due to a lack of UN access. Human rights groups have criticized China for abuses in Xinjiang, where the Uyghur population faces oppression. Despite repeated international offers, Thailand's reluctance to challenge China resulted in deportation.
          </p>
