          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">How can a French nuclear shield work?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">France has always prioritized independence in its nuclear deterrence strategy, including during the Cold War. It developed its nuclear capability to avoid dependency on the US. NATO obligations do not bind Franceâ€™s nuclear policy. France has maintained a clear stance on nuclear deterrence as a dissuasive measure for European defense within NATO.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">Yet, the shifting US support and Trump's reluctance to defend Europe heighten calls for Europe to take more control of its security. French President Emmanuel Macron expressed his <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-08-03-2025-bq1-4-willingness-to-open-discussions" target="_blank">willingness to open discussions</a> about the possibility of a European nuclear deterrent if Europe seeks greater autonomy in defense.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">It would involve extending Franceâ€™s nuclear deterrence capabilities to protect European nations, especially those without nuclear arsenals. The shield would operate under the principle of deterrence and only be operated by France. The idea is to offer protection through the threat of nuclear retaliation if any European nation under the umbrella were attacked.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">Friedrich Merz of Germany suggested there could be potential for shared nuclear capabilities between France and the UK (the two European nuclear powers). This could involve joint nuclear exercises, coordination of strategies, and possibly integrating both countries' nuclear arsenals into a common European defense framework.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">The limitation of the plan is that it is expensive. It could also lead to disagreements among other European countries. It can be particularly consensus since France would only make the final decisions. While it could help Europe have autonomy in its defense and a nuclear umbrella, the limitations should be weighed to ensure it's executed well.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
